BEIJING, Nov 5 (Wang Xiaoyan) Under the current wave of "mass entrepreneurship and mass innovation", more and more science and technology companies are beginning to attach importance to patent research and development and related protection work, dig deep into the potential value of patents and occupy market leadership.
Similarly, there are also many science and technology enterprises in the licensing of patented technology, the use of patented technology and other aspects of the infringement storm.
At the end of 2017, Tan Wei, He Zhanghong and Lai Bin, from Guangdong Province, filed a complaint with the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court against Beijing Xiaoorange Technology Co. Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Little Orange Technology), the developer of the "drip travel" APP, the operator drip travel technology Co. Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as drip travel) and the seller Guangdong Pacific Internet Information Services Co. Ltd. (hereinafter referred to as Guangdong Pacific) on the grounds of patent infringement.
The three plaintiffs requested the court to order that the three defendants immediately stop the manufacture, sale, promise of sale and use of the plaintiff's patent.
On October 30, 2018, the China Referee Instrument Network published the "First Instance Civil Order of Tan Wei, He Zhanghong and Beijing Xiaoorange Technology Co. Ltd. and other disputes over infringement of patent rights for inventions", revealing the details of some of the cases in which APP was sued for patent infringement.
The three plaintiffs held that the patentee and inventor of the patent for the "mobile terminal-based carpool service system and method", and that the whole operation process of the application of the "downwind car" in the "drip travel" APP corresponded to the technical plan for the patent protection involved, which constituted a patent infringement.
However, during the court's ruling, Xiao Orange Technology held that Guangdong Pacific was not a suitable defendant. It only provided free downloads of the APP "drip travel" on the Internet, did not implement the patent method involved, there was no direct or indirect infringement and should not be listed as a defendant in the case.
Second, the place of infringement in this case is not in Guangdong.
According to the law, the place of infringement of the patent involved should be the place where the patent method involved was fully implemented. Therefore, an objection was raised to the jurisdiction of the court and a request was made to transfer the case to the court of the defendant's place of residence, the Beijing Intellectual Property Court, for trial.
The Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court held that the defendant, Guangdong Pacific, had provided the alleged infringement of APP products on its network platform, and that it was not inappropriate for the plaintiff to list the defendant, Guangdong Pacific, as a defendant.
And the defendant Guangdong Pacific domicile in Guangzhou, under the jurisdiction of the Guangzhou Intellectual Property Court.
The defendant, Xiao Orange Science and Technology, argued that the case should be transferred to the Beijing Intellectual Property Court for trial. On the basis of insufficient evidence, he rejected the objection raised by the defendant, Xiao Orange Technology Co. Ltd., to the jurisdiction of the case, and borne the cost of accepting the case of jurisdictional objection.
At present, the other trial of the case has not yet been announced, the reporter will also pay close attention to the follow-up details of the drip travel patent infringement case.
Interview with the Chief Executive Officer of the Australian Federal Scientific and Industrial Research Organization: Australia-China scientific and technological cooperation has achieved remarkable results
"China's science and technology have developed rapidly over the past few decades, and Australia and China can achieve fruitful results by working together in the field of science." he said.
Larry Marshall, chief executive of the Australian Federal Organization for Scientific and Industrial Research, told China News Agency in an interview in Beijing that from combating climate change to cooperation in the "Sky Eye" project, Australia-China cooperation in the field of science and technology has shown great vitality.
As the largest national scientific research institution in the Australian Federation, CSIRO has made a number of innovative research achievements in the fields of oceans, energy, biology, materials and astronomy that have attracted worldwide attention.
CSIRO has maintained close cooperation with scientific research institutions such as the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
"It's a lasting friendship that contains a tradition of trust in partners and long-term cooperation." Marshall said.
In May this year, China's 500-meter spherical radio telescope, the "China Sky Eye", installed the world's first 19-beam L-band receiver.
The most advanced 19-beam feed receiver in the world has been jointly developed by Chinese and Australian scientists.
Mr Marshall said the successful development of the receiver was based on years of technical accumulation by CSIRO, which would increase the speed of FAST travel by five to six times when it was launched, while also expanding more scientific observation targets.
"This is a force that CSIRO has contributed to FAST."
In addition to the above-mentioned cooperation, CSIRO also has close cooperation with Chinese scientific research institutions in the construction of square-kilometer array radio telescopes, the development of new fuel technologies, energy conservation and emission reduction.
"In the past, scientific research has tended to focus on the problems of the past century, and more scientific research is needed to solve the problems ahead." he said.
Marshall believes that Australia and China are complementary in the field of scientific development, while both countries face a series of challenges in their development.
For example, extreme weather is frequent around the world, droughts and floods have led to reduced food production, and food shortages have seriously affected human development.
At the same time, problems such as population explosion, aging and chronic diseases are also serious challenges.
"The cooperation between Australia and China in recent years has been mainly focused on solving these current problems." he said.
Marshall said that the International Southern Hemisphere Marine Research Center, jointly built by CSIRO and the Qingdao National Laboratory of Marine Science and Technology, focuses on observing El Ni ñ o and La Ni ñ a phenomena, studying the relationship between the two and extreme weather, and establishing early warning facilities for extreme weather. The new varieties of cereals developed by CSIRO and the Chinese Academy of Sciences to overcome extreme weather can also alleviate food shortages caused by extreme weather.
"In the current environment, scientific and technological innovation is difficult to complete on its own, requires very high costs and there are many problems to be solved, so cooperation is particularly important today." he said.
Mr Marshall said the closer the cooperation, the more likely it was to make a breakthrough, which was the significance of strengthening cooperation between Australia and China under the "one-way" framework.
"Strengthening bilateral cooperation is mainly scientific and technological cooperation for us." he said.
Marshall said, for example, that CSIRO has recently developed a gold purification method that does not use cyanide. Because the traditional cyanide gold purification method is very harmful to the environment, many countries are hoping to find a way to purify gold that is less environmentally polluted.
"We are willing to introduce this technology into China, which is one of the results of our participation in the 'Belt and Road' cooperation." he said.
