BRUSSELS, Sept 28 (Reuters) -The European Union took a non-stand-off stance against Italy on Friday after Italy defied European Union demands and surprised markets with a large budget deficit plan, but the European Union may take a more aggressive stance if it sticks to too bold goals.
Italy's Eurosceptic government is targeting a budget deficit of 2.4% of gross domestic product over the next three years, suggesting that there has been no debt reduction in the face of deficit reduction requirements alone.
"We have no interest in the crisis between the executive committee and Italy," Moskovesi, the European Union's executive committee on economic affairs, said on Friday, responding cautiously as EU proposals and sanctions could have little impact on Italy.
EU officials and diplomats still hope that market forces will persuade Italy to adjust its budget plan before it is formally presented to the EU's executive committee in mid-October.
The euro fell to its lowest level in nearly two weeks on Friday after the government announced its plans, while Italian bond yields hit their highest level in three weeks.
If the deficit target remains unchanged by the October deadline, the EU's executive committee could veto Italy's draft budget, something the executive committee has never done to any country.
Speaking at a meeting in the Latvian capital Riga later on Friday, the vice-president of the European Union's executive committee, East Blovsky, said Italy's current fiscal plan "does not seem to be in line with the Stability and Growth Pact," referring to the EU's fiscal rules.
But he did not say how the EU would react.
