Reporters learned from the Ministry of Finance on the 30th that the four departments of the Ministry of Finance, the State Administration of Taxation, the National Development and Reform Commission and the Ministry of Commerce have recently jointly issued a notice that, in order to further encourage overseas investors to invest in China, the scope of application of the policy of not collecting advance income tax on the profits distributed by overseas investors from resident enterprises in China for domestic direct investment has been expanded from foreign investment incentive projects to all projects and areas that are not prohibited from foreign investment.
The policy is in effect from January 1, 2018.
The notice makes it clear that direct investment by overseas investors with a share of profits includes equity investment such as capital increase, new construction and equity acquisition by overseas investors with a share of profits, but does not include the addition, transfer and acquisition of shares of listed companies other than eligible strategic investment.
If an overseas investor may, in accordance with the relevant provisions, enjoy the policy of not collecting income tax in advance but does not actually enjoy it, he may, within three years from the date of the actual payment of the relevant tax, apply for the recovery and enjoyment of the policy and refund the tax already paid.
Not only that, but if an overseas investor enjoys the prescribed treatment of the policy of not collecting advance income tax for the time being, the reorganization of the invested enterprise meets the conditions for special reorganization, and the tax treatment is actually carried out in accordance with the special reorganization, he may continue to enjoy the treatment of the policy of not collecting advance income tax.
In order to ensure that the profits earned by overseas investors are actually used for direct investment, the notice stipulates that if the profits used by overseas investors for direct investment are paid in the form of cash, the relevant funds shall be transferred directly from the accounts of the profit distribution enterprise to the accounts of the invested enterprise or the assignor of equity, and shall not be turned around in other accounts inside and outside the country before direct investment; if the profits used by overseas investors for direct investment are paid in non-cash forms such as physical objects and securities, the ownership of the relevant assets shall be transferred directly from the profit distribution enterprise to the invested enterprise or the equity transfer party, and shall not be held on behalf of other enterprises or individuals before direct investment.
The notice also requires the tax authorities to strengthen follow-up administration in accordance with the law.
If an overseas investor has enjoyed the policy of not collecting income tax in advance for the time being, and if he does not meet the prescribed conditions after follow-up management and verification by the tax authorities, he shall, in addition to being the responsibility of the profit distribution enterprise, be deemed to have failed to declare and pay enterprise income tax in accordance with the relevant provisions, and shall be investigated for the responsibility for delayed tax payment in accordance with the law, and the time limit for delayed payment of tax shall be calculated from the date of payment of the relevant profits.
The U.S. Food and Drug Administration (FDA) said on Friday it would no longer allow imports of raw materials produced by China's Huahai pharmaceutical industry and preparations made from the company's raw materials.
A drug previously produced by the Huahai pharmaceutical industry has been recalled for containing possible carcinogens.
The European Medicines Agency said it was considering further action on other ingredients produced by the plant.
The FDA said imports were stopped after major production process problems were found during an FDA inspection of the pharmaceutical factory in the Huahai pharmaceutical industry.
The FDA also said it would ban imports until the Huahai pharmaceutical industry discovered how the impurities were produced and improved its quality control system.
"The company is taking a positive attitude and strong measures to rectify the problems in the official U.S .-European inspection, and the company is very surprised and sorry for the official handling and results of the U.S .-European inspection," the company said in a statement on the company's website on September 29.
In the current complex market environment, the company expressed concern.
At present, the company is organizing a team, including professional lawyers, to communicate and file a complaint with U.S. and European Union officials in accordance with the relevant procedures in order to resume production as soon as possible.
SHANGHAI, Sept 29 (Reuters) -The China Securities Regulatory Commission announced late on Friday that it had approved the initial application (IPO) of China People's Insurance Group Co. Ltd. in accordance with legal procedures.
But the SFC's official micro-letter public number did not disclose the size of the IPO.
China People's Insurance (1339. HK) filed an application with the CSRC as early as September 29 last year to issue up to 4.599 billion A-shares, with plans to list on the Shanghai Stock Exchange.
According to pre-disclosure materials previously published by the SFC, the number of new shares applied for by the company does not exceed 9.78% of the total share capital after the listing, and does not include any shares that may be issued under the over-allotment option.
The funds raised will be used to enrich the company's capital.
On April 9 this year, the SFC announced the prospectus (declaration draft) of China People's Insurance.
According to the prospectus, before the A-share issue, the total share capital of the People's Insurance Corporation of China was 42.424 billion shares. Assuming that 4.599 billion A-shares were issued and the option of over-allotment was not exercised, the total share capital of the group would not exceed 47.023 billion shares after the A-share issue, of which 38.296 billion A-shares and 8.726 billion H-shares.
On June 5, the China People's Insurance IPO application passed the Development Review Committee.
As of December 31, 2017, the Ministry of Finance held 70.47% of the total share capital of China People's Insurance and the Social Security Foundation held 10.2%.
After China People's Insurance issues shares in A-shares, the Ministry of Finance's stake will be diluted to 63.58% and the Social Security Foundation's stake will be 9.2%.
As of Friday, China People's Insurance H-shares closed at HK US $3.52, up 1.44% on the day.
