Xinhua News Agency, Fuzhou, October 1 (reporter Tai Xiaoan) October 1, the Regulations on the Safety Administration of High-speed Railway in Fujian Province were officially implemented.
The regulations state that within 500 meters of each side of the wire of the high-speed rail power line, it is prohibited to lift and fly kites, balloons, Kong Ming lights, aircraft and other empty floating objects and small aircraft.
It is stipulated that, on the basis of the Railway Law of the People's Republic of China, the Regulations on the Administration of Railway Safety and other superior laws, and in accordance with the geographical and climatic characteristics of Fujian Province, supplementary provisions shall be made on the prohibitions and restrictions affecting the safety of high-speed rail, the construction and construction of high-speed rail lines and the planting of trees shall be standardized, the main body and scope of supervision of high-speed rail shall be further clarified, and the duties and legal responsibilities of law enforcement supervision shall be clarified.
In response to the high winds along the coast of Fujian Province and the fact that light construction (construction) materials and light floating objects along the high-speed rail line are blown into high-speed rail to affect safety, the regulations stipulate that it is prohibited to lift and fly kites, balloons, Kong Ming lights, power umbrellas, aircraft and other empty floating objects and small aircraft within 500 meters of each side of the wires of high-speed rail power lines.
In addition, the owner or user of light objects such as plastic huts, color steel plates and sunshade nets along the high-speed rail line, as well as light objects such as low-altitude floats and plastic protective film produced during the construction process, shall take reinforcement and protection measures to prevent them from endangering the safety of high-speed railways.
In view of the characteristics of Fujian Province in hilly areas and the large number of high-speed railway tunnels, the regulations require the construction of mountain ponds, reservoirs, dykes, the excavation of river courses, trunk channels and the drilling of wells within 200 meters of each side of the central line above the high-speed rail tunnel that may affect the safety of the tunnel, and the opinions of railway construction units or railway transport enterprises shall be sought.
At the same time, those responsible for violating the Provisions shall be ordered by the public security organ to make corrections; if the circumstances are serious, the unit shall also be fined not less than 5,000 yuan but not more than 10,000 yuan, and the individual shall also be fined not less than 200 yuan but not more than 500 yuan; if the circumstances are serious, the unit shall also be fined not less than 10,000 yuan but not more than 30,000 yuan, and the individual shall also be fined not less than 500 yuan but not more than 1,000 yuan.
If a loss is caused, it shall be liable for compensation according to law.
It is understood that with the rapid development of railway construction, the high-speed railway mileage of 200 km / h and above in Fujian Province has now reached 1,516 km / h, and the city-to-city motor vehicle has been realized. It is expected that the railway lines of 200 km / h and above in Fujian will reach 2,150 km / h in the next five years.
The implementation of this provision will standardize the safety management of high-speed rail in Fujian Province, further implement the responsibilities of local government departments, coordinate railways and local forces, work together to ensure the safety of high-speed rail, and improve the safety prevention and control system of high-speed rail in Fujian Province.
HONG KONG, Nov 5 (Reuters) -China's largest beer producer, China Resources Beer (Holdings) Co. Ltd. (0291. HK), announced on Monday that it would buy six breweries set up in the mainland by Heineken / Heinegan (HEIN.AS) and all issued equity in Heineken Hong Kong through its China Resources Snowflake Beer, at a total cost of about HK US $2.355 billion.
At the same time, the company has signed a Trademark Licensing Association with Heineken, which authorizes China Resources Xue to use the relevant Heineken trademark to produce, market, distribute and sell licensed products in mainland China, Hong Kong and Macao for a period of 20 years, after which it will be renewed on the same terms and conditions for 10 years at a time until the termination clause of the trademark licensing agreement is terminated.
China Resources Beer announced in August that its direct controlling shareholder, China Resources Group (Beer) Co. Ltd., had reached an equity partnership agreement with Heineken involving about HK US $28.5 billion.
At the same time, China Resources Beer and Heineken have reached a long-term strategic partnership arrangement, which includes the acquisition of Heineken's existing operations in China, Hong Kong and Macao, and the integration of China Resources Beer's beer business in China.
This transaction is the further implementation of the cooperation agreement.
China Resources Beer said the deal with Heineken provided the group with an important strategy, long-term development and value enhancement opportunities to expand into the high-end beer market, and that the long-term partnership between the two sides would be highly complementary.
China Resources Brewery closed at HK US $28.85 on Friday, down nearly 4.5% in the past month.
Number of people killed or as many as thousands after Indonesia's powerful earthquake and tsunami-China New Network
According to comprehensive reports, a 7.5-magnitude shallow earthquake struck the Indonesian island of Sulawesi on September 28, triggering a 6-meter-high tsunami.
The National Disaster Response Department announced on September 30 that the death toll had risen to 832, mainly in the capital, Palu, and the county of Tongara, near the epicenter.
Vice President Kara noted that the death toll could reach as many as thousands as casualties have not yet been counted in some of the disaster-stricken areas.
The powerful earthquake and tsunami that struck Indonesia's Central Sulawesi province on the afternoon of September 28 have killed 832 people.
Thousands of buildings collapse 2.4 million people hit
The Palu disaster was devastated, with thousands of buildings collapsing and multiple roads breaking, and authorities said an estimated 2.4 million people were affected.
A hotel along the local coast collapsed and only 24 guests escaped safely, with an estimated 50 to 60 people trapped in rubble. Calls for help were heard from time to time at the scene, and rescue workers successfully rescued a young woman on September 30.
The search and rescue process was slow as authorities were unable to use heavy machinery to remove the rubble to ensure the safety of the trapped people.
A shopping mall in the city also collapsed, and hundreds of residents rushed to the scene, waiting for news from friends and relatives.
Many residents use social platforms to send letters to find lost friends and relatives.
Rescue efforts begin after a hotel collapsed in the Indonesian city of Central Sulawesi Baru on September 30 local time.
Palu 10,000 people to be rescued 5 foreigners unaccounted for
Authorities said about 10,000 people were waiting for rescue in the city of Palu, scattered across 50 locations.
It is reported that 71 foreign people were in Palu at the time of the earthquake, 66 of whom are temporarily known to be safe, including 21 Chinese citizens, while the remaining two French, two Malaysian tourists and one South Korean are unaccounted for.
The Chinese Embassy in Indonesia is working through various channels to understand and verify the situation of Chinese citizens in the disaster-stricken areas, and has not received any reports of casualties among Chinese citizens.
Communications in Donggara County, near the epicenter, were still disrupted and 11 people were temporarily known to have been killed, but no further details were available.
According to footage from the scene, the coastal areas and ports of Donggara County were severely damaged, a large number of buildings were swept away and bodies were scattered everywhere, and Red Cross rescue teams were on their way to the area to search and rescue.
Indonesia's president visits disaster and says reconstruction efforts will begin as soon as possible
The roads in Palu and Dongara were severely damaged, and only aircraft carrying relief supplies were opened at Palu Airport on 30 September to allow relief supplies and personnel to arrive as soon as possible and remove the seriously injured.
A number of local hospitals are still without power, and the injured have to be treated outdoors.
More than 10,000 victims were admitted to reception centres, and some were afraid to return home for fear of aftershocks, preferring to spend the night outdoors.
Following the collapse of a prison in Palu in the earthquake, which caused hundreds of prisoners to flee the prison, more than a hundred prisoners in Tongara County took advantage of the chaos caused by the earthquake, and prisoners set fire to the detention center.
Indonesian President Zoko, who visited Palu on 30 September to inspect the disaster, noted that it was very difficult to resolve a large number of problems in a short period of time, including the resumption of communications.
He called on the victims to be patient and said the authorities would begin reconstruction as soon as possible.
On the other hand, Indonesia's finance minister announced that the government had allocated 560 billion dong for disaster relief.
A human case of H5N6 avian influenza confirmed in Guangdong Province
The Health Bureau said that according to the latest report from the Mainland health department, a human case of H5N6 avian influenza had been confirmed in Guangdong Province.
The Health Bureau called on residents to avoid contact with birds and pay attention to personal and food hygiene.
According to the data, the patient, a 22-year-old male, now lives in Baiyun District, Guangzhou City, Guangdong Province. He developed fever and other symptoms on 25 September. He was admitted to hospital on 26 September. He is currently being treated in isolation in hospital and is in critical condition.
The patient had slaughtered and eaten live poultry before the onset of the disease.
Since April 2014, there have been confirmed cases of H5N6 avian influenza in Sichuan, Guangdong, Yunnan, Hubei, Hunan, Anhui and Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region.
The Health Bureau will continue to maintain close contact with the health departments of the country and neighbouring regions and the World Health Organization to closely monitor outbreaks in various places and in Australia.
To prevent human infection of avian influenza, the Health Bureau urges the public to pay attention to the following:
Avoid contact with birds or their secretions and excreta. If in contact, wash your hands immediately;
Do not buy or carry unquarantined birds;
Do not eat undercooked bird meat, internal organs, blood products and eggs;
Pay attention to personal hygiene and wash hands frequently;
If you have symptoms such as fever, cough and breathing difficulties, you should wear a mask, seek medical treatment as soon as possible, and explain to your doctor the history of travel and animal contact.
