The Indonesian island of Sulawesi was hit by a powerful earthquake and tsunami on September 28, causing serious damage to several cities along the coast, with the latest news showing that the death toll has risen to 1,200, foreign media reported.
The town of Donggala in the city of Palu, near the epicenter, was reportedly hit by two rounds of tsunamis, and authorities believe the death toll will continue to rise as the "golden 72 hours" of rescue pass.
Rescuers carry an earthquake survivor rescued from under the rubble of a restaurant in Palu, Central Sulawesi Province, Indonesia, September 30, 2018 local time.
Officials from the disaster relief department said the tsunami brought large waves of up to 6 meters, and the impact of the earthquake and tsunami exceeded previous estimates.
Hundreds of people are understood to have been celebrating the festival on the beach in Palu at the time of the earthquake and tsunami, with many killed when they were swept away by large waves.
Officials said the tsunami hit the shore at 800 kilometers per hour and many buildings and infrastructure were destroyed.
He said thousands of homes, hospitals, shopping malls and hotels collapsed, and mudslides triggered by the tsunami cut off a major highway in Palu.
A bridge across a coastal river collapsed in Sulawesi.
On September 30 local time, Indonesian President Zoko visited the city of Central Sulawesi Palu, where the earthquake occurred.
Indonesian President Zoko, who visited the disaster area on September 30, said he had sent troops to assist in the search and rescue and called on the victims to be patient.
Zoko pointed out that the rescue operation was difficult because of a shortage of heavy machinery and manpower.
He learned that there was a lack of water, food and fuel in many parts of the disaster area, and that many merchants had been closed after the earthquake and had sent aircraft to airdrop supplies.
He called on the victims to be patient and stay in their original position waiting for rescue.
Search and rescue workers in the city of Palu said they heard a cry for help from a collapsed hotel in the city, but some people needed to save people with their bare hands because there was no heavy machinery to remove the rubble.
Indonesian Vice President Kara said the death toll from the earthquake and tsunami could eventually rise to thousands after power and communications were cut off in some areas, causing information to be blocked.
