The new U.S .-Mexico-Canada trade deal will retain U.S. President Trump's ability to implement the threat of a 25% tariff on imported cars, while essentially exempting passenger cars, pickup trucks and auto parts imported from Canada and Mexico from paying tariffs, according to a trade agreement subsidiary arrangement released on Monday.
If Trump imposes so-called "Chapter 232" tariffs on cars for national security reasons, both Mexico and Canada would have a tax-exempt passenger car quota of 2.6 million vehicles exported to the United States each year.
Under the ancillary arrangement, pickup trucks produced in both countries will receive full tariff exemptions.
If Trump imposes tariffs on cars, Mexico will receive a tax exemption quota of US $108 billion a year for auto parts and Canada will receive a quota of US $32.4 billion.
Both quotas are well above the current level of production in both countries, providing room for growth in their exports.
WASHINGTON / MEXICO CITY, Sept 28 (Reuters) -After days of debate, U.S. President Trump's administration and Canada are making practical efforts to resolve trade policy differences, raising hopes that the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) is expected to maintain the form of a three-way agreement, Mexico said on Friday.
Despite the lack of details, the apparent progress was enough to prompt the governments of Mexico and the United States to abruptly halt plans to publish the text of the two-party trade agreement and give Canada more time to join the agreement.
Mexico's president-designate, Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador, told reporters in Mexico that the U.S. government had made new counter-proposals to the Canadian government and said he would continue to push for all three countries to participate in NAFTA.
Mexico's economy minister, Ildefonso Guajardo, said the submission of the text of the U.S .-Mexico trade agreement to Mexican and U.S. legislation had been delayed because the Canadian and U.S. governments were "very seriously" trying to reach an agreement.
"In the next 48 hours, we will know whether we will reach a text of the three-way agreement or have to publish the text of the two-party agreement." Guajardo said.
Guajardo said his U.S. and Canadian counterparts "specifically requested" a delay in the release of the text.
A spokesman for the Office of the U.S. Trade Representative (USTR) did not comment on the text of the U.S .-Mexico trade agreement or the U.S .-Canada consultations.
Officials from the Canadian prime minister's office and the foreign minister's office did not respond to requests for comment on the counter-proposal.
Two lions play together at a conservation center on the outskirts of Pretoria, the South African capital, and it is difficult to see any anomalies, but they are unique, foreign media reported.
"This is the first young lion ever to be born by artificial insemination-the first pair in the world." the University of Pretoria announced.
School scientists are working on the reproductive system of female African lions.
Ganswinter, director of the Institute of Mammal Research at the University of Pretoria, said the two cubs, born on August 25, one female and one male, were quite healthy and normal.
After 18 months of intensive trials, his team finally made the breakthrough.
"We collected sperm from a healthy male lion." Ganswinter told the media.
Next, the researchers artificially inseminated the lioness when the hormone levels in her body reached the right level.
"Fortunately, the result was successful." Mr Ganswinter said.
He said the researchers "made several attempts, but unexpectedly, it didn't take much effort".
He said the breakthrough could be repeated, and scientists hope to use the technology to save large endangered cats.
According to the International Union for Conservation of Nature, lions have become extinct in 26 African countries, and the total number of surviving wild lions has fallen by 43% over the past 20 years, leaving only about 20,000.
African lions are listed as vulnerable by the group.
"If we don't do something for this animal, they will face extinction." Ganswint said.
He said the new technology did not need to allow lions to be raised, but simply injected sperm into a fertile lioness, as has been done in North America and Europe for captive elephants.
South Korea's exports fell the most in more than two years in September, but analysts blamed the decline on fewer working days and said global demand for South Korean goods remained strong despite rising trade tensions between China and the United States.
Indeed, South Korea's average daily exports increased last month.
In addition, initial value data released earlier showed double-digit growth in exports in the first few weeks of September before the long holiday.
South Korea's exports fell year-on-year in September, the biggest year-on-year decline since July 2016, more than the 5.7% decline forecast by 11 analysts surveyed by Reuters.
Initial values released on Monday showed exports stood at US $50.6 billion in September, down from US $51.2 billion in August.
South Korea's exports to China rose 7.8% in September, expanding for the 23rd month in a row, despite concerns that a growing U.S .-China trade dispute could hurt other export-dependent Chinese neighbors.
South Korea's exports to the United States fell 11.8% as sales of oil products fell.
Overseas sales of South Korean memory chips and petroleum products rose 28.3% and 13.5%, respectively, despite concerns that the so-called "super-cycle" of chips may have peaked.
"However, the impact of the trade conflict will be difficult to avoid, as South Korea's exports are heavily dependent on the U.S. and Chinese markets." he said.
Imports fell 2.1% to US $40.8 billion, also less than the 3.1% increase forecast in the Reuters survey.
The initial value of the trade surplus in September was US $9.7 billion, up from US $6.9 billion in August.
The Ministry of Industry says global manufacturing will remain buoyant thanks to the United States and European Union countries, which is a plus for South Korean exports.
"Higher export prices caused by higher oil prices will also benefit exports in the second half of the year." the statement said.
"But the continuation of the trade conflict between the United States and China, coupled with increased market volatility after the U.S. interest rate hike, is a negative pressure on exports." he said.
On average, exports per working day rose to US $2.6 billion in September, compared with US $2.1 billion in August.
South Korea's Mid-Autumn Festival falls on September 24-26, so there are only 19.5 working days in September, four days less than in the same period last year.
South Korea's exports rose 4.7% in January-September from the same period last year.
South Korea's manufacturing activity recovered in September, according to the Nikkei / Markit purchasing managers' index, but was supported by domestic orders as orders from China and Japan fell, threatening to cloud the outlook for other exports.
