Nagoya, Nov 5 (Reuters) -Japan's central bank is aware that a long-term ultra-loose monetary policy could squeeze profit margins in financial institutions and could destabilize the country's banking system, President Kuroda Kuroda said on Monday.
But he said the Bank of Japan needed to maintain its massive stimulus package while keeping a close eye on the pros and cons of its policies, given low inflation and uncertainty in overseas economies.
"The Bank of Japan fully recognizes that the strength of financial institutions will be increasingly affected under continued monetary easing," Kuroda said in a speech to business leaders in Nagoya.
He said the banking system could be volatile in the event of a serious negative impact if financial institutions were more active in taking risks to make up for the narrowing of profit margins caused by years of low interest rates.
"Although these risks are not significant at the moment, the central bank will closely monitor the situation and encourage financial institutions to take the necessary measures," he said.
The minutes of the Bank of Japan's meeting, released earlier on Monday, showed that at its September interest-rate meeting, the Bank of Japan's policy committee discussed the rising cost of long-term easing.
The minutes show that one member said that if the economy continues to expand, "the Bank of Japan has more room for policy flexibility in the future."
The minutes showed that another member said the committee should discuss how long the Bank of Japan could maintain the stimulus, given the limitations of the policy's duration.
Kuroda said the Bank of Japan would assess the financial risks posed by easing, as well as the uncertainty surrounding Japan's economic outlook, which could affect global demand as a result of trade frictions between China and the United States and rising protectionism.
"The impact of such problems on the Japanese economy is limited for the time being," Kuroda said.
"But how the problem continues, the impact on the Japanese economy is likely to grow," he added.
"There is a need for sustained strong monetary easing, while considering the positive and negative effects in a balanced way," Kuroda said.
While the drawbacks of the aggressive stimulus program have increased, such as long-term low interest rates eroding the profits of financial institutions, low inflation has forced the Bank of Japan to maintain the program.
The Bank of Japan maintained monetary policy last month; Mr Kuroda ruled out a near-term interest rate hike in the face of the risks posed by a global trade war dispute.
The corporate logo on a Tesla electric car in Cardiff, U.S., June 1, 2018.
Under a settlement, Tesla Motor Co. and its Chief Executive Officer Masque have agreed to each pay a US $20 million fine to financial regulators, and Masque will also resign as chairman of the company but remain CEO.
The settlement will put an end to two months of turmoil at Tesla.
The settlement of securities fraud charges, revealed by the Securities and Exchange Commission on Saturday, will give investors a sigh of relief.
Investors had feared the protracted legal battle would only further hit the electric car company, which is still losing money.
The SEC on Thursday sued Masque for fraud, saying its August 7 tweet misled investors.
The tweet said he was considering privatizing Tesla for US $420 a share and had secured financing.
The SEC said the tweets were virtually unfounded and that the market turmoil they triggered hurt investors.
Investors and corporate governance experts said the agreement could strengthen Tesla, which has been hit hard by Musk's recent behavior.
Steven Heim, head of asset management at Boston Common, said the settlement should have put Masque under more supervision and did not take "devastating" measures to drive him out of Tesla.
The asset management company holds shares in Tesla's battery maker Panasonic.
Under the proposed agreement, Tesla must appoint an independent chairman, two independent directors and a board of directors to develop controls over Musk's external communications.
"It is in the best interests of our market and our investors, including Tesla shareholders, that this matter be resolved expeditiously on agreed terms," SEC Chairman Clayton said in a statement.
Thursday's allegations led to an evaporation of about US $7 billion in Tesla's market value, which stood at US $45.2 billion on Friday, down from GM's US $47.5 billion.
In the settlement, the SEC withdrew its request to remove Masque from the helm of the company.
Many investors said the penalty would be catastrophic.
"I think this is the best possible outcome for all concerned," said Ivan Feinseth of Tigress Financial Partners, who gave Tesla a "neutral" rating and said the SEC's punishment was a "lighter punishment" for Masque.
"It's important to Tesla that he remains CEO."
Neither Masque nor Tesla acknowledged or denied the SEC's allegations in the settlement and did not immediately respond to a request for comment.
The settlement agreement still needs to be approved by the court.
