All 46 kinds of supervision certificates in Inner Mongolia import and export links realize network verification-China New Network
China New Network Hohhot November 5 (reporter Li Aiping) Hohhot Customs said on the 5th that from this date, except for special circumstances such as the need for confidentiality, all 46 regulatory certificates in the local import and export links have been verified on the Internet.
Inner Mongolia enterprises can declare the relevant documents to the Customs in a paperless manner, avoiding the problems of on-site running, paper applications and repeated submission in the past.
It is understood that the preparation time of documents refers to the preparation time of all kinds of documents needed for the import and export link before the declaration of customs declaration. It is a major factor affecting the overall customs clearance time. In order to reduce the customs clearance time and reduce the customs clearance cost, the documents must be reduced.
Previously, there were 86 kinds of regulatory documents that needed to be verified by the Customs in the import and export chain, involving 19 departments.
It is reported that this time, in accordance with the principle of "cancellation that can be cancelled, merger that can be merged, and exit port verification that can be withdrawn from port verification", and relying on the "single window" platform for international trade, the Customs and 16 other license-issuing organs have been systematically docked and data interconnected, thus achieving more data running roads and fewer errands for enterprises.
The Customs said that in the past, enterprises had to go back and forth to and from the on-site office hall of the relevant departments to submit paper applications, the process was long and it was not possible to track the audit status in real time.
Enterprise users can now log on directly to the "single window" portal to apply online.
After the examination and approval of the license-issuing department, the certificate will be transmitted electronically to the Customs, and the automatic comparison with the customs declaration data will be realized in the customs clearance process, and the results of the intelligent verification and examination will be fed back to the enterprises through the "single window", thus realizing the full-process online processing of the declaration, examination, customs clearance and feedback of the regulatory documents.
Exports of Korean ginseng chicken soup to China soar 20-fold in four years or related to the increase in empty-nested youth-China New Network
Analysis of the 20-fold increase in exports of Korean ginseng chicken soup to China in 4 years: related to the increase in empty-nested youth
South Korea's exports of chicken soup to China exceeded US $100,000 last year, up about 20 times from 2013 four years ago, the ROK news agency reported on Friday.
According to the analysis, this increase is related to the increase in the number of empty-nested young people in China, which has led to the hot sale of convenient food, as well as the increase in young people's attention to nutritious food.
The data was released by the Korea Agricultural and Aquatic Food Circulation Commune (aT) on 5 days.
Last year, South Korea's exports of ginseng chicken soup to China reached US $103.339 million and weighed 218.59 million kilograms, up 2,094% and 3668.8% respectively from 2013.
According to the analysis, the increase in sales of South Korean ginseng chicken soup in China is related to the increase in the number of empty-nested young people driving the hot sale of convenient food, as well as the increase in young people's attention to nutritious food.
As of this year, China's one-person households have exceeded the 200 million mark and are expected to increase to 30% of the total population by 2020, and local food companies have also targeted "single-meal people" to launch a variety of convenient food.
In addition, the analysis said bird flu was the biggest factor preventing ginseng chicken soup from taking root in the mainland Chinese market.
aT said there was an outbreak of bird flu in South Korea from November 2016 to April last year, and authorities completely banned the export of ginseng chicken soup to China, leading to a sharp decline in exports.
Exports of ginseng chicken soup to China reached US $840,000 in 2016, and exports plummeted to US $100,000 last year due to bird flu.
