At a recent public meeting of the Security Council on the Korean Peninsula held at United Nations Headquarters in New York, different voices from all sides on the issue of sanctions against North Korea once again highlighted the "unchanged" two points on the peninsula issue.
U.S. Secretary of State Pengpeo has insisted that sanctions against North Korea will not be lifted until the Korean peninsula is fully denuclearized.
Russian Foreign Minister Sergei Lavrov, for his part, stressed the principle of "responding to action with action," noting that "the weakening trend of sanctions should be the same as the steps taken by North Korea on the road to gradual nuclear disarmament".
There is no doubt that the parties concerned should continue to implement the Security Council resolution on the DPRK in a comprehensive, complete and accurate manner, but pressure is not an end. The implementation of sanctions and the promotion of a political settlement are the requirements of the Security Council resolution.
As Chinese State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi said, in view of the current positive developments in inter-Korean and inter-Korean relations, China believes that it is necessary for the Security Council to consider the timely launch of reversible provisions, thus encouraging the DPRK and all parties concerned to take greater steps towards denuclearization.
Looking back, the denuclearization of the peninsula and every progress in the peace process required sufficient political courage from all sides.
At present, in the face of the growing expectations of the international community to promote a political solution to the issue on the peninsula, all parties concerned should, in particular, show political vigour, make political decisions, implement their commitments, resolve difficult problems, continue to take steps towards each other, promote the process of denuclearization of the peninsula in parallel and establish a peace mechanism on the peninsula, so as to jointly create permanent peace on the peninsula.
The people's government of Ji County, Linfen City, Shanxi Province, reported on the first day that during the National Day, the Hukou Falls Scenic Area of the Yellow River, located in the county, will maintain a relatively high water level and will not have the conditions for opening up.
In order to ensure safety, the scenic area was temporarily closed during the National Day.
The Hukou Falls of the Yellow River is the second largest waterfall in China and the largest yellow waterfall in the world.
At this point, the Yellow River is running, the stone walls on both sides of the Taiwan Straits are steep, and the estuary is as narrow as the Hukou, forming the spirit of "a pot of the Yellow River".
According to reporters, June-October of each year is the flood season of the Yellow River. Starting from July 12, 2018, due to the high water level of the Yellow River, the Hukou Scenic Area of the Yellow River in Shanxi Province has been closed, so the Hukou Scenic Area has been closed for nearly a month.
Ni Yufeng, chief engineer of the Hukou Scenic Area Management Committee, told the media that it was the longest period of high water levels in the Yellow River in nearly 20 years. "It has not been so long before. Our flood season is closed for four days in 2017, and this year is nearly a month."
It is understood that the Hukou Falls Scenic Area of the Yellow River in Shanxi Province was originally intended to welcome the Golden Week of the 11th National Day, but also increased personnel arrangements and vehicle maintenance in advance, and even the employment of temporary staff have been put in place.
According to the Notice on Doing a Good Job in Flood Control of the Yellow River during the National Day, issued by the Office of the Yellow River Flood Control and Drought General Command, Qinghai, Gansu, Ningxia, Inner Mongolia, Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Shandong Province are required to do a good job in flood control of the Yellow River during the National Day.
At present, the flow of the main stream of the Yellow River is large, with the flow of the upstream river remaining at 2000-3,000 cubic metres per second, the flow of the middle reaches of the river remaining at 2500-3,500 cubic metres per second, and the flow of the downstream river remaining at 3,000 cubic metres per second.
Health centres and health stations provide influenza vaccination services during National Day holidays
The Health Bureau has ordered 150,000 doses of the four-price influenza vaccine for 2018-2019 this year. At this stage, priority is given to free vaccination for high-risk people. To facilitate residents to be vaccinated against influenza during the holidays, health centres and health stations under the Health Bureau provide vaccination services from 9 a.m. to 1 noon during the National Day holiday (1 and 2 October).
In addition to the above measures, the health centres and health stations under the Health Bureau have extended their influenza vaccination services from Monday to Friday to 8 p.m. since the launch of the programme. As at 4 p.m. on 30 September, 4,158 people had been vaccinated, up from 3,714 in the same period last year.
The free vaccination targets include the following Macao residents: persons aged 6 months to under 18, aged 50 and over, pregnant women, all people with chronic diseases, including obese people (i.e. those with a BMI of 30 or more), as well as staff of institutions, nurseries, kindergartens, primary and secondary schools, all health workers, and Macao residents working in betting casinos.
At the same time, if the Health Bureau considers it necessary to vaccinate other persons, including the public sector, the Health Bureau will contact the relevant organisations on its own initiative to obtain the list and arrange the vaccination by the Health Centre.
To facilitate vaccination and reduce the waiting time for vaccination, the Health Bureau will send medical staff to secondary schools, primary schools, kindergartens and nurseries in Australia between October and December this year to vaccinate young children, small and medium-sized students, teachers and staff against influenza. In addition, the Health Bureau will arrange for staff to carry out group vaccination in homes for the elderly and the disabled, the public sector or other institutions with a large number of people.
Students and young children who have not been able to take part in the group vaccination can be vaccinated at the vaccination station or health centre of the Earl of Yan General Hospital with a Macao Resident Identity Card, a Health Bureau User Card, a Influenza Vaccination Card (if any), a student card, a staff card or a vocational certificate from 3 December 2018.
The Health Bureau has reminded residents that people who have been vaccinated against the 2017-2018 flu between September 2017 and August 2018 will still need to be vaccinated against the new season of the flu from September 2018, as the flu antigen ingredients contained in the 2018-2019 northern hemisphere flu vaccine have been updated to target seasonal influenza in the northern hemisphere for the winter of 2018-2019 and the summer of 2019.
The peak period of influenza in Macao usually occurs from January to March of each year, later than in temperate regions (such as northern China and Japan). The Health Bureau calls on high-risk people, such as the elderly, children, pregnant women, obese people and people with chronic diseases, who are more likely to develop complications after contracting influenza, as well as those who are in frequent contact with high-risk people, to be vaccinated as soon as possible.
