TOKYO, Oct 1 (Reuters) -Confidence among Japan's big manufacturers hit its lowest level in more than a year in the September quarter as rising raw material costs and a series of natural disasters affected production, putting pressure on companies, according to the Bank of Japan's quarterly short-view survey released on Monday.
The survey shows little evidence that escalating global trade frictions have hit the confidence of big manufacturers.
But the risk of a full-scale trade war has hit business prospects and could threaten capital spending.
Active capital spending is a bright spot in the Japanese economy.
The survey raises questions about the Bank of Japan's view that robust economic expansion will help push inflation to accelerate to its 2% target, despite signs that companies are gradually passing on costs to customers.
"In the face of concerns raised by a global trade war, confidence among manufacturers has stagnated due to slowing exports and weak factory production," said Nan Wuzhi, chief research fellow at the Institute of General Cooperation in Agriculture and Forestry.
"Confidence is still high. And because corporate profits are improving and prices are rising, I don't think confidence will continue to decline." he said.
The short-view survey showed that the large manufacturing boom judgment index fell to positive 19 in September from positive 21 three months ago, the third consecutive quarter of deterioration.
The median market estimate is positive 22.
The large non-manufacturing boom judgment index fell to positive 22 in September from a positive 24 in June, the first deterioration in eight quarters.
The Reuters survey was positive 22.
According to the survey, the large manufacturing and non-manufacturing boom judgment index is expected to hold steady in December.
Investors were unconcerned about the decline in the short-term corporate boom judgment index, with Japan's Nikkei. N225 rising to a 27-year high on Monday as the continued depreciation of the yen helped improve the export profit outlook for Japanese companies.
Capital expenditure is robust.
Despite the decline in corporate confidence, the latest short view highlights the soundness of corporate capital spending plans, helped by renewing capacity, and increased investment in robotics and automation to cope with labor shortages caused by an ageing population.
Large companies plan to raise capital spending by 13.4% in the current fiscal year, which ends in March 2019, according to the central bank's short-view survey.
In the previous short-view survey, it was 13.6%.
Mr Nan said all corporate capital spending plans to grow by 8.5% this fiscal year, close to the pace of Japan's bubble economy.
"Given that small companies have raised their profit estimates from now on, there is still room for further growth in capital spending, but much depends on the impact of a trade war on corporate confidence." he said.
The short-view survey showed an increased ability of companies to pass on costs, with the output price index of large companies at a positive 7, a decade high, an encouraging sign of progress in Japan's efforts to combat deflation.
The index, which measures the employment status of large enterprises, hit minus 23, the most tight level since 1992, highlighting the tightening of the job market.
Japan's economy rebounded in the second quarter from a contraction in January-March this year, benefiting from strong corporate spending.
But the escalation of trade frictions over the summer and the disruption of supply chains by natural disasters have clouded the outlook for Japan's export-dependent economy.
