The 69th International Astronautical Congress opens in Germany-China New Network
Bremen, Germany, October 1 (Xinhua) -- The 69th International Astronautical Congress kicked off on October 1 at the Bremen Convention and Exhibition Center in Germany, attended by more than 6,300 astronauts, representatives of space agencies and enterprises, experts, scholars and young students from all over the world.
Speaking at the opening ceremony, the President of the International Astronautical Federation, Jean-Yves Le Gal, said that the global space industry was no longer attended by only a small number of countries and institutions, and that the number of participants this year had increased significantly from the previous session, indicating that more and more institutions and people were joining it.
He called on all countries to strengthen cooperation and innovation and jointly promote the development of the space industry.
Zhang Kejian, Vice Minister of Industry and Information Technology of China and Director-General of the National Space Administration, introduced China's space program at the exchange and said China would expand international cooperation in the field of space and contribute to the space industry of mankind.
Representatives of relevant institutions such as the China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation and the China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation, as well as some private enterprises, attended the meeting to showcase the latest achievements of China's space industry, including launch vehicles, satellites and space science and technology applications.
The International Astronautical Congress, which has been held annually since 1950, is the largest event in the world's aviation industry.
The five-day conference was co-sponsored by the International Astronautical Federation, the International Academy of Astronautics, the Centre for Applied Science and Technology and Microgravity Research of the University of Bremen and the International Society of Space Law.
BEIJING, Nov 5 (Reuters) -The Canton Fair shows that China's foreign trade situation remains complex and severe, with 80.6% of companies expecting exports to be better or flat for the whole of 2018 than the previous year, according to a press release issued by the China Foreign Trade Center on Sunday.
However, taking into account the external environment in which the cost of comprehensive factors such as domestic raw materials and labor continues to rise and the impact of trade frictions between China and the United States has increased, the exhibitors also believe that the export situation next year is not optimistic.
At the closing press conference of the 124th Canton Fair, Xu Bing, deputy secretary-general of the Canton Fair, press spokesman and deputy director of the China Foreign Trade Center, said that the number of overseas buyers and export transactions at the Canton Fair had fallen slightly year-on-year.
There were 189,812 buyers from 215 countries and regions, down 1.11% year-on-year.
Exports traded 206.494 billion yuan (US $29.86 billion), down 1% year-on-year.
In terms of the market, transactions with Japan, the 10 ASEAN countries, the BRICS countries and South Korea increased by 74.4%, 11.4%, 7.2% and 2.5% respectively, while traditional markets such as the United States, Australia, Canada and the European Union fell by 30.3%, 8.9%, 7.3% and 0.8% respectively.
In terms of industry, means of transport, machinery and equipment, construction and decorative materials, consumer electronics and information products and sanitary equipment increased by 24.8%, 21.1%, 20.0%, 15.1% and 7.6% respectively, while textiles, clothing and household appliances fell by 13.0% and 6.7% respectively.
Xu Bing said that, as a barometer and weathervane for China's foreign trade, the participation of buyers at the Canton Fair and the export transaction data show that China's foreign trade development still faces many uncertain and unstable factors next year.
However, with the in-depth progress of supply-side structural reform and the recent introduction of policies and measures in the areas of "six stability" by the state and local governments, the new momentum of China's foreign trade development is accelerating its accumulation and new progress has been made in the diversification of the enterprise market, all of which are important foundations and strong conditions for the development of foreign trade.
"Taking into account all factors, it is expected that China's foreign trade imports and exports will maintain steady growth throughout the year, with further improvement in quality and efficiency." Xu said.
China's General Administration of Customs reported that dollar-denominated exports rose 14.5% year-on-year in September and imports rose 14.3% year-on-year, with a trade surplus of US $31.69 billion in September, with export growth and trade surplus both the highest since February.
Despite the escalating trade frictions between China and the United States, China's export performance in September still significantly exceeded expectations, strong external demand, and the devaluation of the RMB exchange rate by companies before the United States imposed tariffs, or the main supporting factors, also show the resilience of China's foreign trade to some extent, but the impact of the China-U.S. trade war on confidence and on the industrial chain is not to be underestimated, and analysts believe the challenges to China's foreign trade are likely to emerge in the 4th quarter or next year.
U.S. fund managers recommended increased cash holdings in September and continued to be cautious as the United States and China began the latest round of import tariffs and the dispute showed no signs of easing, according to a Reuters survey.
But asset allocation in North America rose to its highest level since June 2017, while positions in the UK, the euro zone, especially emerging markets, fell, according to the 12 fund managers involved in the survey.
Global stock allocation averaged 56.6% and bonds accounted for 35.5%, largely in line with last month's survey.
