More than 90% of Brazilian women voters said the presidential candidate did not take into account the needs of women.
More than 90% of Brazilian women do not believe that presidential candidates take into account the needs of women, according to data released recently by Brazil's National Institute of Geography (IBGE), according to the South American Overseas Chinese News Network.
The number of women in Brazil has now reached 107 million, and if women from all over Brazil are brought together to form a country, the country will be ranked 13th in the world, more than twice the population of Spain, the report said.
In Brazil, women accounted for 52% of the total number of voters and men for 48%, and although the proportion of women in the electorate was very high, women accounted for only 10% of the country's Congress.
Of the world's 193 countries, Brazilian women are ranked only 154th in political participation, higher than Arab countries.
After more than 20 years of power struggle, Brazilian women still have not succeeded in gaining their rights.
Natalia Mori, a Brazilian sociologist, points out that the reason for this phenomenon is the result of a combination of ancient patrilineal societies, racism and capitalist values.
"Politics should have been for nationals to claim civil rights, identity, access to public goods and form the same society by multiple social groups, but Brazilian politics is the monopoly of a certain group and the majority of the population is not represented." he said.
A previous study by the Brazilian Institute of Locomotive Research also noted that 94% of Brazilian women do not feel that elected politicians can represent their rights, 90% do not agree with the decisions made by politicians and 93% do not agree with the current government's governance policies.
"We need to reverse the underrepresentation of women in parliament, and Brazil's political system is still affected by inequality. So far, there is still serious gender, class and racial discrimination in Brazil's political sphere." Natalie Murray said.
Despite the lack of women's rights, most Brazilian women still believe in the power of democracy.
According to the survey, 76% of women think they can make a difference in democratic elections, and 72% are interested in politics.
In addition, 55% of women believe that democratic politics is the best way to expose women to less prejudice.
