Terminal T2 of Guilin Shuangjiang International Airport in Guangxi was officially opened on the 30th.
Zhao Leqin, secretary of the Guilin Municipal Committee of the Communist Party of China (CPC), said that the opening of the new terminal could meet the annual passenger throughput demand of 12 million, build a new advantage in Guilin's air traffic, and is of great significance to further improve the modern three-dimensional traffic pattern of Guangxi's river-sea linkage, sea-rail intermodal transport, water-land parallel and air-port connection.
Guilin is expected to receive more than 90 million visitors this year.
The expansion of Terminal T2 and the supporting facilities of Guilin Two Rivers International Airport is a major public welfare project to celebrate the 60th anniversary of the founding of Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, as well as a landmark project for the construction of Guilin's international tourist resort.
The project began in December 2015 with a construction area of 100,000 square metres and a total investment of 3.258 billion yuan. When completed and opened, it will meet the annual passenger throughput of 12 million, 1.012 million sorties and 95,000 tons of cargo and postal throughput.
On the same day, more than two hundred flights took off and landed at Terminal T2 of Guilin Shuangjiang International Airport.
The design of the new terminal is inspired by the mountains and rivers of Guilin. It is like a "mountain and water crown" from a distance. It is like the "dragon ridge terraces" and the layered eaves of residential buildings in northern Guangxi. It is reflected in the mountains and rivers of Guilin.
According to the report, the new terminal of Guilin Airport can meet the peak flow of nearly 4,000 people entering and leaving Hong Kong per hour. It has used "smart airport" technical means such as intelligent baggage sorting system, security integration platform and face recognition, and has planned a business district covering a variety of businesses, such as catering, department stores, tax exemption and leisure and entertainment.
