A three-way trade agreement between the United States, Canada and Mexico will bring new opportunities to 500 million people.
The United States, Canada and Mexico have reached a three-way trade agreement, which will be known as the "USMCA" (the three-nation agreement between the United States, Mexico and Canada), according to a joint statement by Canadian Foreign Minister Freeland and U.S. Trade Representative Wright Hezer published on the Canadian government's website, according to foreign media reports.
Earlier, Canadian television station CTV News, citing senior U.S. sources, said Canada and the United States had resolved their differences and reached an agreement on the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA).
The agreement reached between the United States and Canada on September 30 will retain the North American Free Trade Agreement as a three-way trade agreement, and the three heads of state will sign a new agreement within two months, the Washington Post reported, citing two sources familiar with the situation.
"Today, Canada, the United States and Mexico have agreed on a new trade agreement-the U.S .-Mexico-Canada Three Kingdoms Agreement (USMCA), which will provide high standards of trade agreements for our workers, farmers and companies, which will lead to freer markets, fairer deals and more sustainable economic growth, which will strengthen the middle class, create high-paying jobs and bring new opportunities to about 500 million people." the statement said.
It is reported that the current North American Free Trade Agreement was signed by the United States, Mexico and Canada in 1994.
After taking office, Trump announced plans to reconsider the agreement and sign a new one.
The three countries began this negotiating process in 2017.
The results of the early Okinawa governor's election, which was held as a result of the death of former Governor Weng Changxiong-zhi, were announced in the early hours of the morning local time, and Yucheng Danny, who opposed the plan to relocate the U.S. military base in Japan, was elected.
The final results of the election, which was counted on September 30, showed that Yucheng received 396.632 million votes, the highest number of votes in the history of the Okinawa Prefecture governor's election and more than 80,000 more votes than its main rival, Zo Hei-chun.
