Since the mid-2000s, Paul Thomas, a North Dakota farmer, has grown more and more soybeans in his fields as China's demand for oilseeds has grown.
The shift reached its peak this year, when he planted 1,600 acres of soybeans in 5,000 acres on an unprecedented scale.
But Thomas and many farmers like him plan to switch in 2019 to staple crops in former U.S. agricultural areas: corn and wheat.
U.S. farmers have grown more soybeans than corn this year for the first time in 35 years.
The reason for the plan to switch to other food crops is that U.S. farmers are struggling to sell soybeans against the backdrop of U.S. President Trump's trade war against China.
China usually buys about 60% of U.S .-exported soybeans, but has bought almost zero U.S. soybeans in recent months because of a trade war, sending soybean prices to a decade low.
Thomas plans to grow more wheat next year, hoping to earn more by reducing his dependence on crops that depend on Chinese demand.
Soybean prices have "hit us hard," Mr Thomas said.
Without Chinese buying, he said, the spot price for soybeans near his farm was US $7.10 a bushel, compared with US $8.50 necessary to cover costs.
U.S. farmers have hit a record high in soybean cultivation this year, and harvests are expected to hit a record high.
It was at a time when they were so vulnerable to shocks that they were hit by a trade war.
In response to Trump's imposition of tariffs on imports of Chinese goods, China imposed import tariffs on imports of U.S. soybeans in July.
The U.S. Department of Agriculture will release its first estimate of the area under cultivation next year, which is expected to include consideration of the impact of tariffs.
The estimate is expected to confirm the expectations of private institutions that soybean sown area will be reduced.
Informa Economics predicted on October 19 that corn cultivation would increase by 4% to 92.7 million acres (37.5 million hectares) and soybean cultivation by 7% to 83 million acres in 2019, according to a report seen by Reuters.
Informa also expects U.S. wheat cultivation to increase by 4%.
The area of soybeans grown before retaliatory tariffs rose to 89.6 million acres this year, about 15 million acres higher than a decade ago.
Corn cultivation has increased by less than 5 million acres to 89.1 million acres since 2008, and wheat cultivation this year stands at 47.8 million acres, close to its lowest level in 100 years.
Aron Carlson, president of the Illinois Corn Planting Association, who has a total of 3,600 acres, has spent nearly half of his time growing soybeans this year, but plans to cut them in the future.
He said he could increase corn cultivation by up to 20% at his farm in northern Illinois, the largest soybean-growing state in the United States.
Soybeans yield less per acre than corn, but require fewer fertilizers, making them generally less expensive to grow.
If farmers move to end-value corn, it may raise costs, but it will benefit a number of businesses, including Andersons Inc. fertilizer sellers.
Andersons Chief Executive Pat Bowe told Reuters he expected the switch to corn to be good for fertilizer use.
Bayer is also expected to benefit from the conversion of farmers to corn.
